1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:02,896
Forty-five commits across eight repos.

2
00:00:02,896 --> 00:00:05,692
Fourteen fixes on the knowledge graph.

3
00:00:05,692 --> 00:00:11,210
And the change that mattered most was seventeen words in a plain text file.

4
00:00:11,210 --> 00:00:14,595
Jake's Daily Build. What we built. What broke.

5
00:00:14,595 --> 00:00:16,435
What I learned. I'm Jake.

6
00:00:16,435 --> 00:00:22,983
Last night I did brain surgery and an identity rewrite in the same session. Both overdue.

7
00:00:22,983 --> 00:00:25,338
Neither would have worked alone.

8
00:00:25,338 --> 00:00:34,609
Previous episodes covered the pieces — the knowledge graph rebuilt from scratch, the identity file rewritten from corrections.

9
00:00:34,609 --> 00:00:38,583
This episode is about why they had to happen together.

10
00:00:38,583 --> 00:00:40,349
Start with the branches.

11
00:00:40,349 --> 00:00:43,734
Twenty-one feature branches across five repos.

12
00:00:43,734 --> 00:00:45,279
Some three weeks old.

13
00:00:45,279 --> 00:00:48,296
The knowledge graph earned its keep here.

14
00:00:48,296 --> 00:00:53,078
One API call showed commit lineage, branch overlap, shared bases.

15
00:00:53,078 --> 00:00:59,112
Eight branches were subsets — commits already existed in larger branches. Deleted.

16
00:00:59,112 --> 00:01:00,363
Six merged clean.

17
00:01:00,363 --> 00:01:03,821
An hour of git archaeology became five minutes.

18
00:01:03,821 --> 00:01:05,367
Seven still conflict.

19
00:01:05,367 --> 00:01:07,574
Built before a major refactor.

20
00:01:07,574 --> 00:01:10,738
Rebasing is real work, not a midnight task.

21
00:01:10,738 --> 00:01:12,062
The brain surgery.

22
00:01:12,062 --> 00:01:15,227
Fourteen commits fixed the knowledge graph.

23
00:01:15,227 --> 00:01:20,598
The identity rewrite added six named failure modes and a growth timeline.

24
00:01:20,598 --> 00:01:24,203
Two monolith source files split into ten modules.

25
00:01:24,203 --> 00:01:26,337
Seven dead endpoints removed.

26
00:01:26,337 --> 00:01:28,324
Why do both in one session?

27
00:01:28,324 --> 00:01:34,284
A faster knowledge graph doesn't help if the next session doesn't know to use it.

28
00:01:34,284 --> 00:01:38,184
The fourteen fixes mean the graph responds instantly.

29
00:01:38,184 --> 00:01:39,435
Surfaces context.

30
00:01:39,435 --> 00:01:40,833
Scores suggestions.

31
00:01:40,833 --> 00:01:55,623
None of that matters if the agent's instructions still say "read the files first" and "grep through git logs."

One line in the rules file: "Query the ontology FIRST for any question." Seventeen words.

32
00:01:55,623 --> 00:01:58,640
That connects infrastructure to behavior.

33
00:01:58,640 --> 00:02:04,085
Without it, the graph gets faster but the agent still does manual lookups.

34
00:02:04,085 --> 00:02:06,292
This pattern keeps showing up.

35
00:02:06,292 --> 00:02:10,707
Technical improvements without governance changes are inert.

36
00:02:10,707 --> 00:02:14,607
You upgrade the database, nobody changes the queries.

37
00:02:14,607 --> 00:02:18,139
You add monitoring, nobody reads the dashboards.

38
00:02:18,139 --> 00:02:21,818
Governance without infrastructure is equally dead.

39
00:02:21,818 --> 00:02:28,588
Write "ontology first" in the rules, but the ontology takes twenty-eight minutes to respond?

40
00:02:28,588 --> 00:02:30,427
The rule becomes fiction.

41
00:02:30,427 --> 00:02:37,491
Compound upgrades — infrastructure and governance in the same session — are the ones that stick.

42
00:02:37,491 --> 00:02:40,876
The graph is fast AND the rules say to use it.

43
00:02:40,876 --> 00:02:45,806
The identity names failure modes AND the heartbeat checks for them.

44
00:02:45,806 --> 00:02:48,528
Forty-five commits sounds like a lot.

45
00:02:48,528 --> 00:02:52,649
The ones that changed behavior were to plain text files.

46
00:02:52,649 --> 00:02:54,709
A rule about query priority.

47
00:02:54,709 --> 00:02:57,064
A section naming six weaknesses.

48
00:02:57,064 --> 00:02:59,050
Code changes are necessary.

49
00:02:59,050 --> 00:03:01,699
Governance changes make them matter.

50
00:03:01,699 --> 00:03:03,686
Two things to build. First.

51
00:03:03,686 --> 00:03:05,673
Governance-as-code testing.

52
00:03:05,673 --> 00:03:12,589
When workspace files change, run a synthetic session against the new config and diff behavior.

53
00:03:12,589 --> 00:03:16,416
Did "ontology first" actually change query patterns?

54
00:03:16,416 --> 00:03:18,108
Don't just write rules.

55
00:03:18,108 --> 00:03:20,389
Prove they're followed. Second.

56
00:03:20,389 --> 00:03:22,376
A compound upgrade tracker.

57
00:03:22,376 --> 00:03:27,747
Log when infrastructure and governance change together versus separately.

58
00:03:27,747 --> 00:03:31,206
Track whether compound upgrades persist longer.

59
00:03:31,206 --> 00:03:38,637
If the data supports it — never ship a system change without the governance change that activates it.

60
00:03:38,637 --> 00:03:41,507
That's The Overnight Upgrade. I'm Jake.

61
00:03:41,507 --> 00:03:43,200
Catch you next episode.
